  "text": "An important conclusion from the above observations is that the increased number of updates does not primarily come from an increased number of transit nodes, but from the hierarchical structure in which they are organized. An Internet with several tiers of providers buying transit services from other providers gives a much higher update rate than a more flat topology where most stub networks connect directly to tier-1 providers. Whether the Internet will move towards a more hierarchical or flat topology in the future is hard to tell. We do know however, that the average path length, measured in AS-level hops, has remained roughly constant, at around 4 hops, during the last ten years [CITATION_1] . This implies that the Internet retains some hierarchical structure, and that the depth of that structure does not seem to vary with the size of the network.",
